title: Evaluated activation cross sections of longer-lived radionuclides produced by deuteron induced reactions on natural titanium

x4freetext: Evaluated activation cross sections of longer-lived
radionuclides produced by deuteron induced reactions
on natural titanium

x4freetext: MGC-20E cyclotron
High purity natural Ti foils, from Goodfellow
thickness: 4.03 micron.
A satack of Ti and Fe foils was irradiated with 10 MeV
deuteron beam of 150nanoA for 1.5 hour.
Fe foils were used for energy degradation and for
checking the energy along the stack. The stack was
irradiated in a Faraday-cup type target holder,
equipped with a long collimator and electron supressor
for precise definition of bombarding charge.
The count rate was kept low so that corrections
for pile up effects and dead time could be implemented
through the acquisition and analyzing software.
The charge on target was first derived from the
Faraday-cup measurement.
Data were collected from 10 independent experiments to
chek the shape of the excitation curve in the low
energy region, below 10 MeV, by using the high energy
part, above 10 MeV, as monitor reaction of the same
natTi(d,x)48V reaction. The shape provided by the 10
independent experiments perfectly agreed the shape of
the measured curve.
above 10 MeV

x4freetext: Decay data were taken from NUDAT2 database.
The uncertainty of the primary beam energy was
0.25 MeV. The uncertainty on the average energy of the
last foil of the stack, due to the uncertainty on the
foil thickness and to energy degradation was estimated
to be 0.5 MeV.
For estimation of standard uncertainty on the
cross section values the individual uncertainties
included in the propagated error are:
* number of target nuclei including
non-uniformity (5%),
* incident particle intensity (5%),
* detection efficiency (5%),
* peak areas including statistical errors (1-5%),
* gamma decay data (1%).
The total uncertainty of 11-13% is obtained as
positive square root of a sum of the contributing
sources in quadrature.
The non-linear effects of the possible uncertainty of
the half-lives were not taken into account.
Error in number of target nuclei including
non-uniformity (5%),
Error in  incident particle intensity (5%),
Error in detection efficiency (5%),
The measured experimental data were compared
with earlier literature values.
Recommended data were given from threshold
up to 50 MeV.
S. Takacs, 2007.
